<TEXT>
while millions of americans were spending last 
easter weekend rushing to finish their taxes members of the main 
house taxation committee were on a taxpayerpaid trip to barbados 
on something like candid camera 
there to discuss a trade bill the lawmakers spent much of their 
time frolicking at the pool being entertained by lobbyists or 
golfing at taxpayers expense unknowingly under the watchful eyes 
of a television news crew 
the fiveday fournight stay at the paradise village and beach 
club came at the end of a 12day official committee trip by 34 
people that also included stops in several south american cities 
the bill 100000 in all 40000 for the barbados portion 
the eight members of the house ways and means committee were met 
and entertained on the caribbean island by lobbyists representing 
insurance and computer companies with interests before the 
taxwriting panel 
what the lawmakers aides spouses and military escorts on the 
trip didnt know is that much of their visit was videotaped by a 
crew from abctvs primetime live which broadcast a report on 
the trip thursday night 
the barbados stop was approved by committee chairman dan 
rostenkowski dill so the lawmakers could research the caribbean 
basin initiative a trade bill before the panel 
according to abc the lawmakers spent less than seven hours in 
business meetings and most of their time relaxing each billed the 
government for 1176 in daily expenses and other expense costs 
even though they received many of their meals free at official 
receptions or those hosted by lobbyists 
on the second day of the trip the lawmakers attended a 
40minute morning meeting on the trade legislation and another 
hourlong meeting later after a luncheon at the prime ministers 
residence according to the network 
by midafternoon the work was done and three members went 
golfing billing their greens fees to the us embassy other 
lawmakers and members of the delegation relaxed at the resort pool 
i think that this idea that the press thinks these trips are 
junkets is absolutely ridiculous one of the three golfing 
lawmakers on the trip democratic rep marty russo of illinois 
told abc the bottom line is we work very hard on these trips 
also on the trip were rostenkowski democratic reps fortney 
stark of california barbara kennelly of connecticut thomas downey 
of new york and george miller of california and republican reps 
richard schulze of pennsylvania raymond mcgrath of new york and 
guy vander jagt of michigan miller is not a member of the ways and 
means committee but was invited on the trip by rostenkowski 
the videotape of the trip shows lawmakers swimming snorkeling 
jet skiing sunbathing and playing football with some of the 
lobbyists 
the lobbyists included two for mutual insurance companies that 
would benefit under tax legislation filed by downey and a former 
top russo aide who now works at a law firm representing comdisco a 
chicago a computer company that would benefit from leigislation 
filed by russo 
until last year russo was on retainer for the same law firm 
coffield ungaretti harris and slavin russos past two financial 
disclosure forms show he received 25000 from the firm in 1988 and 
1989 
downey who only participated in the barbados portion of the 
trip and was videotaped with one of the insurance lobbyists before 
the rest of the delegation arrived told the program there was no 
discussion of legislation with the lobbysits 
he said he suspected the lobbyists were there so that they can 
see us in an informal setting 
russo said he did not believe his legislation presented a 
conflict because of his past role at the law firm he said his 
former aides role as a lobbyist had nothing to do with his 
introducing the legislation 
i introduced a bill for the computer industry because i think 
the computer indistry in this country is being unfairly taken 
advantage of he said 
abc said the other lawmakers on the trip declined to be 
interviewed for the segment abc traveled to barbados ahead of the 
delegation after receving a tip about the trip and the crew 
videotaped the activities of the delegation using handheld 
cameras 
