<TEXT>
six typhoid fever outbreaks nationally this year 
equals the number reported in all of the 1980s federal health 
officials said 
one outbreak in washington state was linked to a large family 
reunion centers for disease control researchers said thursday the 
locations of the other outbreaks werent disclosed but the 
researchers said two were reported in restaurants one was linked 
to homecooked food one was traced to imported shellfish and the 
other had an unknown origin 
typhoid fever once a dreaded disease is most commonly linked 
to poor sanitation it is spread via contaminated food and water 
its now rare in the developed world 
symptoms include fever headache pains and nausea 
preliminary cdc reports show 406 cases reported nationwide with 
10 weeks remaining in the year if that rate continues the 1990 
total could reach 503 the most since 1983 
the cdc received reports of only six typhoid outbreaks or 
clusters of cases from 1980 to 1989 
the family reunion outbreak occurred at a gathering of 293 
people from five states in skagit county wash the cdc said at 
least 17 people at the reunion were dagnosed with typhoid fever 
the average illness lasted 20 days 
health investigators found that three food items served at the 
reunion were linked to the outbreak a person who prepared one of 
them tested positive as a carrier of the typhoid bacteria 
typhoid is preventable by a vaccine recommended for americans 
traveling to areas with typhoid problems such as central and south 
america africa india and southeast asia the vaccine has been 
reported to cause severe side effects in some cases including high 
fever but an oral vaccine approved earlier this year promises 
fewer side effects 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

