<TEXT>
japans proposal to deploy troops overseas is being 
dragged down by fierce resistance in parliament and if it fails 
prime minister toshiki kaifus job could go with it analysts say 
polls published thursday showed kaifus popularity in a sharp 
dive largely because of the perception that he is waffling on a 
decisive issue for japan in the persian gulf standoff 
that negative image has been magnified by televised debate in 
parliament over the deployment bill an acutely sensitive issue in 
this nation kaifu is seen repeatedly shifting position under 
attack from opposition members who seem to have enough votes to 
defeat the bill 
kaifu has done it with spectacular incompetence said 
garrett scalera president of the tokyo institute of policy 
studies i think his days are numbered 
the newspaper yomiuri shimbun published a poll thursday showing 
that support for kaifus cabinet has fallen by 10 points since last 
month to 498 percent most of the drop was attributed to the prime 
ministers wavering statements in parliament 
another leading newspaper the mainichi shimbun put his support 
at 35 percent a drop of 6 points the polls did not give a margin 
of error 
in july a yomiuri poll had kaifus popularity at 625 percent 
the highest rate for any postwar cabinet 
those results in part reflected the 59yearold prime ministers 
strong showing at the houston economic summit and us trade talks 
earlier in the year the gulf crisis however has been a far more 
serious test for kaifu and hes responded with a series of 
flipflops 
after the aug 2 iraqi invasion kaifu announced a financial aid 
package for the gulf but declared the nations selfdefense forces 
sdf would not go when japans senior security partner the 
united states expressed unhappiness over the decision kaifu did 
an aboutface 
the result was a proposal to deploy support troops under the 
united nations umbrella that opened a pandoras box that japan has 
preferred to keep shut whether to reconsider its postworld war ii 
constitutional ban on using force overseas 
kaifu himself didnt want to send the sdf from the very 
beginning his indecisiveness is the reason why the bill is so 
unpopular said seizaburo sato a tokyo university politics 
professor and former adviser to two prime ministers 
if kaifu really firmly believed it was necessary for japan to 
send the selfdefense forces the people would accept it 
faced with antideployment sentiment at home as well as in other 
asian countries kaifu has been at best confusing at worst 
selfcontradictory under intense grilling from leading opposition 
members at a special session of parliament in recent weeks 
on wednesday for example he was pressed to clarify what 
cooperation japan could offer to gulf forces already there kaifu 
answered he could not say at present despite previous assertions 
that his peace cooperation corps would be involved in 
transportation medical aid and other specific noncombat 
activities 
and he dismissed concerns that corps members might face armed 
conflicts overseas despite some forecasts the gulf could soon 
erupt in war 
some experts say kaifus political weakness in japans ruling 
liberal democratic party a factor since he was installed in august 
1989 has finally come home to roost 
the prime minister elected from a small party faction as a 
compromise candidate has been repeatedly embarrassed in recent 
weeks as powerful ldp politicians have edged him out of the 
headlines by making independent diplomatic initiatives in north and 
south korea and elsewhere 
some analysts say those politicians conservatives themselves 
who want a strong deployment bill see kaifu as a sacrificial lamb 
on the issue 
few now believe the overseas deployment bill can be passed by 
the time parliaments special session ends nov 10 
with kaifus credibility bound up in the proposal the only 
thing that might save him from resigning if the bill fails is the 
lack of a consensus candidate to replace him before his term ends 
in november 1991 
</TEXT>
