<TEXT>
frustration over the political and 
economic impasse gripping nicaragua has flared into a wave of 
bombings looting land takeovers and armed skirmishes 
president violeta chamorro and a 14party coalition swept to 
victory in february ending more than a decade of revolutionary 
sandinista rule with promises of economic recovery and peace 
but the sandinistas by far the largest and bestorganized 
pressure group in the country have used negotiations and muscle to 
keep control of the army and police and to block the governments 
economic programs 
in view of the governments relative impotence some of the 
sandinistas enemies are threatening to take the situation into 
their own hands 
the episcopal conference the influential organization of 
nicaraguas 11 roman catholic bishops warned thursday against the 
deteriorating situation 
there is a growing frustration in broad sectors of the 
population regarding the use and future of the vote cast last feb 
25 and of the implementation of measures and programs different 
from that for which they voted the conference said in a 
statement 
on wednesday about 300 demobilized contra rebels and 
sympathizers surrounded the sandinistacontroled police station in 
the small town of rio blanco demanding the removal of the police 
chief 
the same day a gathering of businessmen government officials 
and independent and sandinista labor unions broke off negotiations 
aimed at developing an economic program after 34 days of talks 
while all sides agree that nicaraguas economy is flattened by 
hyperinflation a fiscal deficit and low production the government 
is being pulled by the demands of leftist sandinistas and rightist 
business groups neither of which seem willing to compromise 
the sandinistas say government proposals to stabilize the 
economy will cause mass unemployment business groups say the plans 
dont go far enough 
the superior council for private enterprise nicaraguas major 
business group claims the government has diluted its plans to 
return property confiscated under leftist sandinista rule 
partial strikes by sandinistaorganized government workers are 
frequent and disruptive their demands range from pay raises to the 
firing of officials appointed by the new government 
many of the 20000 contra rebels who finished demobilizing in 
june are unhappy with what they say are broken government promises 
for land 
former rebels have taken over sandinista cooperatives in remote 
parts of nicaragua and shootouts between exrebels and sandinista 
security forces have left more than 12 people dead and scores 
wounded 
last week the government declared a state of emergency in the 
remote atlantic town of puerto cabezas where demobilized indian 
rebels looted government warehouses accusing the officials of 
stealing donations intended for them three people were wounded and 
21 people arrested 
earlier this month at least 200 exrebels took over the hamlet 
of waslala in northern nicaragua forcing out sandinista police and 
soldiers in clashes that left four dead 
around the same time bombings temporarily silenced two managua 
radio stations one sandinista and the other fiercely 
antisandinista 
