<TEXT>
pacific island leaders meet with president bush 
on saturday worried that their ocean is becoming a us chemical 
weapons dump and their tiny nations are slipping down the list of 
us aid beneficiaries 
flying in from across the pacific to confer with bush are the 
presidents or prime ministers of nine remote and economically 
vulnerable countries ranging from papua new guinea population 36 
million to nauru a midocean dot supporting 8000 people 
bush who arrives friday scheduled the unprecedented session to 
coincide with a swing through honolulu to campaign for patricia 
saiki a republican congresswoman vying with democratic incumbent 
daniel akaka for a us senate seat 
for months pacific islanders have expressed concern about plans 
to destroy chemical weapons from us far eastern and european 
bases at a giant new incinerator on johnston atoll a usheld 
ring of islands 825 miles southwest of hawaii 
as bush and the pacific leaders meet in two hours of talks 
followed by lunch the latest shipment of such munitions will be 
nearing johnston atoll 
two us navy ships carrying 100000 artillery shells packed 
with nerve agents the us armys stockpile from west germany are 
expected to reach the atoll next month 
the south pacific forum an organization of regional 
governments has complained the plan could make the region the 
toxic waste disposal center of the world 
the environmental group greenpeace usa went to court to block 
the operation but a federal judge last month rejected the 
challenge 
tests of the incinerator are to end late next year and 
fullscale incineration is expected to begin in 1992 the united 
states and soviet union have agreed to destroy such weapons by 
1997 
geoffrey a henry cook islands prime minister and chairman of 
the pacific islands conference another regional organization said 
johnston atoll will be on their minds when he and the other leaders 
meet with bush 
in my view the top concern is the enviromental issue henry 
said in a telephone interview 
a us administration official said in washington on wednesday 
that islanders have been reassured that the destruction of these 
chemical weapons will be carried out in an environmentally safe 
manner 
but the official speaking on condition of anonymity said 
johnston atoll and other environmental issues are expected to be a 
major topic at the honolulu talks 
island leaders also want the united states to sign the south 
pacific nuclear free zone treaty banning use testing dumping and 
storage of nuclear weapons and nuclear waste in the region the 
soviet union australia and new zealand are among the nations that 
have signed the protocols 
besides the cooks papua new guinea and nauru the island 
governments represented at the summit with bush will be fiji 
kiribati the marshall islands the federated states of micronesia 
tuvalu and western samoa 
the islanders may also seek reassurances from bush on longterm 
prospects for us development assistance they fear that the 
budget crisis in washington might mean cuts or even the elimination 
of us aid 
because they are ministates us funds for them could get 
squeezed out said michael p hamnett a pacific scholar at the 
university of hawaii 
the aid programs an estimated total of 16 million yearly for 
the islands could be reduced because of american commitments to 
eastern europe central america and the middle east henry said 
we understand the rest of the world needs attention and we in 
the pacific have to learn to live with that he said nothing 
is happening in our region that requires the attention of the 
united states 
