<TEXT>
deep cuts in star wars spending in 1991 will 
delay a white house decision on deploying an antimissile shield by 
at least two years the projects director says 
henry cooper who took over as head of the project just last 
summer has determined that because of the budget squeeze he 
cannot provide the scientific basis for a deployment decision 
before the end of 1994 at the earliest 
shortly after he took office in 1989 bush told the pentagon he 
wanted to be able to decide what kind of star wars defense to build 
by the end of his term in 1992 
coopers spokeswoman maj carolyn channave said wednesday that 
cooper had reached this conclusion on the basis of the 1991 defense 
bill approved on wednesday by the house and expected to be passed 
by the senate this week cooper was not available for comment she 
said 
the spending reduction of about 800 million to a fiveyear low 
of 289 billion also is likely to mean the end of development 
work on some of the exotic weapons that gave the strategic defense 
initiative its star wars nickname 
one expected casualty is the freeelectron laser once 
considered one of the most promising efforts to harness intense 
beams of light for weaponry the powerful laser would bounce its 
beam off a series of orbiting mirrors to zap ballistic missiles 
over the soviet union destroying them moments after liftoff more 
than 700 million has been spent on this project over the past 
seven years 
the budget also may sound the death knell for the xray laser 
powered by the detonation of a hydrogen bomb the xray laser was 
envisioned as firing multiple beams of radiation across space to 
destroy soviet missiles work on this weapon which does not yet 
exist has cost about 1 billion in recent years 
bush had requested 46 billion for sdi for the 1991 budget year 
that began oct 1 the decision by congress to sharply reduce the 
spending total does not mean the project is dead but its pulse is 
slowing and its shape is changing 
sdi was launched by former president reagan in march 1983 and 
became a cornerstone of american defense policy reagan promoted 
the project as a way of rendering nuclear weapons obsolete but the 
bush administration has abandoned the idea of erecting an 
impenetrable antimissile shield 
cooper disclosed earlier this month that he is restructuring sdi 
to attempt to win congressional support for building a limited 
defensive shield one that could stop as many as a couple hundred 
ballistic missiles but not protect against an allout soviet 
nuclear attack a threat most see as receding 
bush said earlier this year that strategic defense was more 
important than ever before but some of sdis most fervent supports 
are now wondering why the president didnt put up a bigger fight 
against congress rush to cut star wars spending 
daniel o graham a former director of the defense intelligence 
agency and chairman of the prosdi group americans for the high 
frontier said the 1991 defense budget deals a devastating blow 
to the project he urged bush to veto it 
bush is not expected to veto the bill in part because defense 
secretary dick cheney said this week he would not recommend 
rejection despite his misgivings on sdi spending 
equally troubling to cooper the sdi director is a provision in 
the bill that would for the first time give congress control over 
how the sdi money is spent cooper has said this will limit his 
ability to apply technologies developed in one area of the project 
such as spacebased interceptors to other areas 
</TEXT>
