two attacks on key military 
garrisons appear to signal the beginning of a major rebel 
offensive but it might not be the sort of onslaught the guerrillas 
initiated out last year 
residents of the capital have been on edge since the end of the 
rainy season the period starting in the fall when most guerrilla 
offensives have begun during the 11yearold civil war 
last november guerrillas mounted an assault in parts of the 
capital that continued for three weeks and was their biggest 
offensive of the war 
military and rebel sources indicate the pattern of this years 
attacks might be different 
instead of entrenching themselves in densely populated 
neighborhoods the guerrillas plan an escalating series of 
hitandrun attacks on selected military targets the sources say 
a more sustained effort to rout the armed forces might follow 
the attacks the sources say 
the new rebel campaign opened with a thunderous 20minute mortar 
barrage early oct 17 on the main air force base at ilopango on 
the citys eastern edge 
nearly two hours of combat between paratroopers and retreating 
rebels ensued the firefight struck panic in residents of the 
eastern neighborhoods where the fighting in last years offensive 
was fiercest 
but by dawn the zone had returned to relative normalcy 
the attack on ilopango left five soldiers wounded and damaged 
six helicopters according to the air force the rebel farabundo 
marti national liberation front said it had damaged 24 helicopters 
the capital was rattled again tuesday afternoon by two powerful 
explosions a botched guerrilla attack on the military compound in 
the citys southern sector that houses the defense ministry and the 
joint chiefs of staff 
both homemade mortar rounds fell some 150 yards short of their 
target onto a private house the mortars killed two children and 
wounded three adults 
rumors of an offensive have been circulating since july the 
army has been on a high state of alert for months cancelling 
leaves stepping up patrols beefing up base security and setting 
up new checkpoints and roadblocks 
hours before the attack on ilopango the defense minister col 
rene emilio ponce said in a televised interview we have good 
information that they the rebels are indeed preparing an 
offensive of a type different from that of last year according to 
our information it is going to be more selective and will involve 
more firepower 
