us senate voted friday to halve the 85 million aid package to el 
salvadors military and promised to cut aid altogether if the 
government withdrew from peace talks 
if the rebelsfail to demonstrate good faith in negotiations 
or launch a major offensive the slashed 425 million would be 
restored 
an earlier version of the bill would have restored the aid if 
the rebels refused a government offer for a ceasefire but it was 
rejected 
the rebels say there is no point in a ceasefire until 
negotiations have achieved major changes in salvadoran society 
they want a drastic purge and reduction of the armed forces in 
exchange for their own demoblization 
the government says it will not agree to measures that undermine 
the armed forces integrity and insists that the military do any 
housecleaning it deems necessary 
