<TEXT>
a new study finds that farmers will be in for 
some harder times under the 1990 farm bill the national farmers 
union says 
the analysis by economist daryll ray of oklahoma state 
university shows that a farmer with a 350acre wheat base and a net 
income of 15787 in 1990 could see income drop more than 1000 in 
1991 based on current prices and costs 
by 1995 the fifth year of the new farm bill the annual 
reduction in net income from current levels would be nearly 4000 
according to the study distributed wednesday by the farm 
organization 
the reduction in net income would result mostly from provisions 
in the legislation that reduce the amount of acreage eligible for 
government deficiency payments 
those are subsidies to make up the difference between market 
prices and target levels the acreage cuts involved a triple 
base option so farmers can plant what they choose on that 
acreage those crops however are not eligible for deficiency 
payments 
specific cuts in the commodity programs were provided in the 
farm bill but were also tied to the passage of the budgetreduction 
measure that is aimed at cutting federal spending by 500 billion 
over the next five years 
the agriculture departments share of that reduction is 136 
billion and includes the cutbacks in commodity price support 
operations cited in the study circulated by the national farmers 
union 
i dont know how anybody who purports to represent farmers 
be they in congress in the administration or in farm and commodity 
organizations could support this farm bill nfu president 
leland swenson said in a statement it will absolutely devastate 
rural america and these numbers show the unfair share of budget 
cuts farmers would shoulder 
in all according to the nfu deficit reduction may cost the 
average taxpayer as much as 100 to 300 per year but farmers who 
also are taxpayers may end up contributing many times those 
amounts because of reduced income 
most farm organizations have been saying all along that the 
136 billion reduction in usda programs over five years will mean 
reductions in net farm income 
the national farmers organization for example said last week 
that the lowprice policies advocated by the bush administration 
were bargaining tools in the current negotiations under the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade 
nfo president devon r woodland said the drive by the 
administration to get the european community to go along with 
subsidy cutbacks will fail and that congress will have to 
reconsider the farm bill after the gatt talks end on dec 31 
the national grange has said the 136 billion cut ordered for 
usda programs represented unilateral disarmament by the united 
states in the trade talks the granges national master robert 
barrow said the costs of trimming the budget deficit should be 
borne more equitably 
rob nooter of the american farm bureau federations washington 
office said wednesday that the farm bill and its tie to the 500 
billion budgetreduction package is certainly going to have an 
impact on farm income 
some of the income lost from reduced deficiency payments will be 
made up by other features of the 1990 farm bill but not all of it 
he said 
