<TEXT>
congress is beginning a gradual winding down 
of us support for covert conflicts in the third world with an 
intelligence bill that curbs money flowing to rebels in 
afghanistan cambodia and angola 
on a voice vote the house on wednesday gave its endorsement to 
the compromise bill which provides roughly 30 billion for 
intelligence activities around the globe and institutes reforms 
growing out of the irancontra affair 
the senate followed suit early today sending the bill to 
president bush rep gerald solomon rny said that while bush 
does not like parts of the measure he may hold his nose and let 
the bill become law 
on the covert paramilitary conflicts the bill reflected a 
growing congressional skepticism about such expensive and thorny 
involvements and the evaporation of ussoviet tensions that was 
the rationale for an american role 
according to sources familiar with the bill and to limited 
sections made public it 
provides that us covert weapons supplies to the unita rebels 
in angola could be suspended if the marxist government in luanda 
agrees to free elections and a ceasefire and the soviet union 
halts its own weapons shipments to the government it would be up 
to the president to decide whether those conditions have been met 
the provision was a scaledback version of restrictions that had 
been adopted by the house during an unusual public debate last week 
on the aid program which is technically secret 
half of the lethal aid would be put into a restricted account 
subject to release only on approval of the congressional 
intelligence committees weapons aid represents roughly half the 
60 million annual us support for the rebels 
suspends the covert aid program to noncommunist rebels 
fighting the moscowbacked government of cambodia the program 
which sources say amounts to about 13 million will be phased out 
early in 1991 and converted into an open program of humanitarian 
aid to the rebels and to other cambodians 
lawmakers are worried that aid to the rebels is finding its way 
to the infamous khmer rouge who were responsible for the killings 
ofmmore than a million cambodians during their rule in the late 
1970s the countrys warring parties are working with the united 
nations to set up a provisional government in december that would 
then organize national elections 
trims aid to the mujaheddin the rebels fighting the 
sovietbacked government of afghanistan from bushs request for 
300 million to 250 million that compares with 280 million last 
year 
the aid also will be split into two sixmonth increments this 
will give an opportunity for the united states to end the 
assistance at midyear if talks between secretary of state james a 
baker iii and soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze result in 
agreement on a mutual aid suspension 
the intelligence bill also includes provisions intended to head 
off a recurrence of a scandal like the irancontra affair which 
came to public attention in 1986 
the section includes a new definition of covert action an 
operation undertaken by the united states in another country to 
influence political economic or military conditions abroad in a 
way that the us role is not acknowledged publicly 
under the new provisions any covert action must be approved by 
the president in advance in writing in a document known as a 
finding the finding must state that the action is necessary to 
support us foreign policy objectives and must be reported to 
congressional overseers in a timely fashion 
the finding also must spell out which us agencies will be 
involved and whether any outside party will be enlisted in the 
operation the covert action may not be used to influence domestic 
political processes or public opinion and may not violate the 
constitution 
in the irancontra affair congressional investigators found 
that a cabal of zealots inside the executive branch had 
commandeered policymaking set up operations outside normal 
government controls and failed to notify congress of efforts to 
trade arms for us hostages in iran and generate money to supply 
the contra rebels in nicaragua 
sen david boren dokla chairman of the senate intelligence 
committee said the provisions in the new bill really put that 
chapter behind us im really pleased that we now have some 
positive tangible results from those long investigations that were 
undertaken it is perhaps the most significant part of the bill 
</TEXT>
