<TEXT>
michael goldsmith an ap foreign correspondent for 
45 years who reported on wars and rebellions in africa asia and 
the middle east has died at a hospital in southern france he was 
68 
goldsmith died wednesday of a massive stomach hemorrhage said 
his doctor at the grasse hospital he suffered a stroke oct 1 and 
was hospitalized again sunday after a relapse 
goldsmiths most recent post was north africa correspondent 
based in paris but traveling frequently earlier he served as a 
news staffer and bureau chief in geneva 
he reported on numerous conflicts in africa southeast asia and 
the middle east and covered olympic games in grenoble france 
montreal seoul and los angeles among others 
mike brought the enthusiam of the cub reporter and the honed 
wisdom of an old foreign service hand to everything he did 
president and general manager lou boccardi said wednesday 
wherever the big story was within his territory or outside 
it when we sent mike there we knew that the story would nestle 
safely in the hands of a pro the temptation is to think of mike as 
among the last of a breed rather i think of him as someone whose 
example assures that within the ap the breed will go on boccardi 
said 
this year goldsmith spent five weeks in liberia covering the 
civil war in that west african nation he was detained and briefly 
beaten by government soldiers on aug 12 
the soldiers threatened to shoot goldsmith and two other western 
reporters as spies after they had crossed on foot through rebel 
lines into governmentcontrolled territory in the center of 
monrovia the capital but they eventually were released 
later in the summer goldsmith attended the venice film festival 
for the premiere of a movie by german director werner herzog about 
the deposed central african emperor bokassa i goldsmith served as 
an adviser on the film and interviewed some of bokassas relatives 
goldsmith was on assignment in bangui covering bokassas 
coronation in 1977 when authorities arrested him and accused him of 
being a spy 
he was beaten unconscious by bokassa two of his sons and a 
group of aides 
after being held a month in the infamous naragba prison 
goldsmith was summoned to bokassas palace where bokassa ranted at 
him for hours before announcing he was releasing him for 
humanitarian reasons 
despite this incident goldsmith keep in touch with the deposed 
emperor while he lived in exile in france 
the associated press managing editors and the overseas press 
club cited goldsmith in connection with the bokassa story 
goldsmith was born in vienna austria in 1921 to british 
parents 
he was educated at london university and served as an 
intelligence officer in the british armys royal ulster rifles in 
world war ii 
he joined ap in 1945 in london and was assigned to 
britishoccupied germany 
following a roving assignment in italy he transferred to geneva 
in 1948 and remained there nearly two decades covering un 
european headquarters and assignments in africa and the middle 
east 
he reported on postindependence turmoil in the congo now 
zaire algeria and south yemen and the construction of the berlin 
wall 
goldsmith also went to vietnam laos and cambodia following the 
1968 tet offensive and then returned to cover the paris peace 
talks 
he covered the 1973 middle east war and continued reporting on 
developments in africa 
in 1980 he went to afghanistan to cover the aftermath of the 
soviet invasion reporting on an antisoviet movement in kabul that 
virtually paralyzed the government 
he is survived by his wife roxanne their son andrew 15 and 
two sons and a daughter from previous marriages martin michael 
and mary 
roxanne is the daughter of the late sam houston johnson author 
of my brother lyndon 
his wife said there will be no funeral and that a memorial 
service will be held in paris at a later unspecified date 
</TEXT>
