<TEXT>
a bill awaiting the presidents signature will 
compel colleges and universities to tell students how many major 
crimes are committed on campus 
it is time to take the mask off the idea that a college campus 
is a completely serene and protected environment said rep 
william goodling rpa a former teacher and principal who was the 
measures house sponsor 
the senate approved the measure by a voice vote wednesday 
sending it to president bush for his signature the bill passed the 
house monday night 
house and senate sponsors of the bill say they believe the 
president will sign it 
thestudent righttoknow and campus security act would 
require federallyaided colleges and universities to report campus 
crime statistics each year to students and employees covered 
crimes include murder rape robbery and auto theft 
information on violent crimes would have to be provided 
immediately and all crime data would be available to prospective 
students on request 
the measure was merged with another bill requiring institutions 
to release graduation rates of all students and students on sports 
scholarships schools would also have to make data available on 
athletic department revenues and expenditures and on racial 
composition of scholarship athletes 
sponsors included sens bill bradley dnj the former 
princeton university and new york knicks basketball star edward 
kennedy dmass and arlen specter rpa 
there is no comprehensive data on campus crime out of 3000 
colleges and universities and 5000 other federallyaided 
postsecondary schools only 352 provide crime statistics to the 
fbi 
surveys show that 80 percent of campus crimes are committed by 
one student upon another and that most of the violent crimes are 
alcohol or drugrelated according to congress 
goodling introduced the bill in september 1989 after being 
contacted by the parents of a 19yearold lehigh university student 
who was raped and murdered in her dormitory room in 1986 the 
assailant also a lehigh student had entered the dormitory through 
an emergency exit propped open by students visiting from another 
dorm 
howard and connie clery of bryn mawr persuaded pennsylvania and 
nearly a dozen other state legislatures to require colleges and 
universities to release statistics on crimes committed against 
students they began pushing for federal legislation last year 
</TEXT>
