congressional negotiators face several key tax 
issues as they work on a compromise deficitreduction bill 
here are some of them according to a proposed compromise 
incorporating elements from both parties exact figures could 
change in the final agreement 
rates the 28 percent top income tax rate on the wealthiest 
600000 americans likely would be raised to 31 percent they would 
get a tax increase effective rates could even be higher depending 
on exemptions and deductions about 4 million couples and 
individuals who now pay a top rate of 33 percent would pay a 
maximum 31 percent and get a tax cut 
deductions a couple or individual could write off only 97 
percent of otherwise allowable itemized deductions on any portion 
of adjusted gross income exceeding 100000 thus a highincome 
taxpayer would lose 300 in deductions for each 10000 of income 
above 100000 this has the effect of raising the top marginal tax 
rate on those people to 32 percent 
exemptions benefits from the 2050 personal exemption allowed 
each taxpayer and dependent would be reduced as taxable income 
exceeds 100000 for single people and 150000 for childless 
couples filing a joint return the exemption would be fully lost 
once income tops 225000 for single individuals or 275000 for a 
couple filing jointly 
each exemption lost would raise the effective marginal tax rate 
by onehalf percentage point the bigger the family the higher 
their marginal rate thus a couple with two children would pay a 
top rate of 34 percent on part of their income the regular 31 
percent rate plus 1 percentage point because of the limit on 
deductions and 2 points by losing their exemptions 
capital gains the maximum tax rate on capital gains which are 
profits from the sale of assets such as investments would be 28 
percent even though wages and other income would be taxed as high 
as 31 percent this would benefit those who pay a top 33 percent 
rate on income including capital gains under present law 
gasoline the 9centagallon tax would be increased by 5 or 6 
cents 
alcohol negotiators already have settled on higher taxes on 
alcoholic beverages tobacco airplane tickets furs and jewelry 
and expensive cars 
