<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has ordered an art dealer 
to return four sixthcentury byzantine mosaics stripped from a 
cyprus church after turkeys 1974 invasion of the mediterranean 
island 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals on wednesday upheld an 
indiana courts august 1989 ruling ordering dealer peg goldberg of 
the indianapolis suburb of carmel to return the valuable religious 
artwork to cyprus 
i think it sends a powerful message in indiana you cannot 
take title to something from a thief you cant just go buy this 
stuff and expect to keep it said john david hoover an 
indianapolis attorney for the republic of cyprus 
art experts viewed the case as a landmark in a growing effort by 
lessdeveloped nations to reclaim and protect national treasures 
the pieces were chiseled from the ceiling of a church in northern 
cyprus an area controlled by a turkishbacked government 
recognized only by turkey 
ms goldberg bought the mosaics from a turk living in munich 
germany for 108 million in july 1988 religious leaders and 
cypriot officials claimed the mosaics were stolen and sued ms 
goldberg for their return 
ms goldbergs attorney joe c emerson would not comment on 
the courts decision wednesday he said he did not know whether the 
art dealer would appeal 
ms goldberg who had argued that she attempted to make sure the 
works were not stolen when she bought them did not return a call 
after messages were left on her answering machine 
chief judge william bauer writing for the court said the 
turkish governments seizure of property in cyprus did not 
invalidate the autocephalous greekorthodox church of cypress 
claims of ownership 
the mosaics pieced together with painted glass about 525 ad 
are fragments of a much larger work on the ceiling of a small stone 
church in northern cyprus the pieces roughly 2 feet square 
depict jesus as a boy the apostles james and matthew and an 
archangel 
they are among only a handful of icons surviving the first few 
centuries of christianity 
various appraisals place the mosaics value between 4 million 
and 6 million hoover said they are being stored in a private 
vault in indianapolis 
the lawsuit was filed after ms goldberg tried to sell the 
mosaics to the j paul getty museum in malibu calif for 20 
million marion true the getty museums curator of antiques 
turned down the offer and contacted authorities in cyprus 
the court ruled that ms goldberg did not check sufficiently 
into the legal ownership of the mosaics before buying them hoover 
said 
