<TEXT>
western europes arms industry its 
orders dwindling in the postcold war era could shrink by nearly a 
third by the mid1990s the stockholm international peace research 
institute said today 
armsmanufacturing companies will be faced with a shrinking 
pie and there is no alternative to reducing existing over 
capacities the prestigious institute said in a report 
the institute predicted that within five years up to 500000 of 
the european industrys 14 million jobs would disappear and arms 
sales will be reduced as much as 30 percent 
the report says the industry is reacting to talks in vienna 
austria on reducing conventional forces in europe the planned 
soviet pullout from eastern europe and the collapse of the warsaw 
pact 
the 71page document was written by armscontrol experts ian 
anthony of great britain anges courades allebeck of france and 
herbert wulf of germany 
it said the persian gulf crisis has provided no new markets and 
orders from developing nations have fallen because they lack hard 
currency to buy expensive modern weaponry 
such big customers as egypt israel and syria are reducing arms 
imports and iraq and kuwait are under an arms embargo 
paradoxically there will likely be a decrease of arms imports 
in the gulf area anthony said adding that it was unlikely 
imports to saudi arabia would rise enough for any substantial 
effect on the arms industry 
one reason he said was that western nations were unlikely to 
support major exports to saudi arabia because of the volatility of 
the middle east 
european nato countries bought new weapons worth 324 billion 
last year during the same period the united states bought arms 
for 718 billion 
the report says 70 percent of the 100 largest european arms 
producers are in great britain germany and france 
the european arms industry grew for years until military budgets 
leveled off in the mid1980s in the years ahead annual military 
budget cuts of at least 2 percent can be expected the institute 
said 
european arms companies started cutting down three years ago and 
some 100000 jobs have been lost already the report says 
the industry is restructuring itself through mergers and 
diversification into civilian production civilian companies are 
being acquired as in british aerospaces purchase of automaker 
rover 
the report lists more than 20 takeovers and eight mergers since 
the beginning of 1989 many deals have been across borders 
including the creation of a french and italian space company 
matra marconi espace 
the institute said companies that generate most of their incomes 
from the arms sector will be heavily affected by the reductions 
but not all sectors of the arms industry will suffer 
the report says western europes future defense is likely to be 
based on fewer men and fewer massive tank and artillery units 
armed forces would consist of smaller highly mobile units equipped 
with hightech weaponry 
arms companies specializing in electronics helicopter 
production and military aircraft appear to have good future 
prospects in addition production of missiles not included in 
armsreduction talks may grow 
