<TEXT>
declining consumer confidence and the persian 
gulf crisis pushed september sales of existing homes down 8 
percent a real estate trade group reported thursday it was the 
slowest pace in nearly three years 
the national association of realtors said resales totaled a 
seasonally adjusted 322 million houses the slowest pace since a 
320 million rate in january 1988 
all regions posted sales declines except for the northeast 
which was unchanged from an already low level the august rate had 
been 350 million 
realtors president norman d flynn said declining confidence in 
the economy has been fueled by uncertainty over the impact of 
federal budget legislation and the persian gulf situation 
consumers dont know what to expect flynn said when 
people dont know whats coming they tend to delay bigticket 
expenditures many of them put their home buying plans on hold 
the south led the sales decline falling 100 percent to an 
annual rate of 126 million units 
in addition to consumer confidence realtors chief economist 
john a tuccillo said the deployment of military troops from 
southern bases to the persian gulf decreased demand for houses and 
upset the local economies 
the military pullout has taken more buyers from the 
marketplace than the ones sent overseas tuccillo said 
companies in those areas that rely on military business are 
hurting the economic fallout has interrupted purchase plans of 
civilians 
the commerce department next tuesday will report on september 
new home sales sales of new homes fell 14 percent in august to a 
550000 annual rate 
thomas holloway an economist with the mortgage bankers 
association said higher interest rates rising unemployment and 
the uncertainty of middle east developments will keep the housing 
market sluggish for months to come 
but holloway said the september existing home sales was not as 
negative as shown on the surface 
noting the jump in sales to 35 million units in august he said 
the average of the two months comes out to 33 million houses 
right in line with the level of sales in the previous four 
months 
according to surveys by the federal home loan mortgage corp 
30year fixedrate mortgages averaged between 1019 percent and 
1022 percent in september the rates generally were higher than 
the average during the first half of the year 
buyers scaled back their purchases partly because of slightly 
higher rates flynn said but economic uncertainty played a 
much bigger role 
the median price of an existing home nationally fell 29 
percent to 94300 the median means half of the homes cost more 
half less 
