<TEXT>
parliament on thursday 
overwhelmingly approved a law to put into private hands about 
100000 small shops and enterprises that were nationalized during 
four decades of communist rule 
the privatization process is a key part of reforms aimed at 
transforming czechoslovakias centralized economy into a 
westernstyle one guided by market mechanisms 
the law was approved by 202 of the 239 deputies present and 
voting the state ctk news agency reported 
finance minister vaclav klaus who presented the draft to the 
legislature wednesday said it was a compromise which cannot 
satisfy all completely 
the measure will apply to some 100000 shops and small 
enterprises with an overall value of about 83 million equivalent 
to nearly half the nations annual budget 
thousands of vendors across the country staged symbolic strikes 
last month demanding they be given first crack at buying the shops 
they wanted to pay up to half the purchase price in installemnts 
spread over a sevenyear period 
the vendors were afraid they would be shut out by people with 
large amounts of capital to invest foreigners or onetime 
communist functionaries who amassed fortunes under the former 
government 
although the government draft would have given employees of the 
enterprises being bought the option of installment payments over 
five years the version approved by parliament scrapped that 
provision 
auctions will be held in two rounds with the first round open 
only to czechoslovak citizens and those who emigrated after the 
communists came to power in 1948 
shops and enterprises which are not sold in the first round will 
proceed to the second in which some foreigners will also be 
allowed to bid 
the bidding will begin at prices determined by the government 
the minimum price acceptable for any shop sold is 50 percent of the 
governmentproposed amount 
if the secondround auction is attended only by czechoslovak 
citizens the minimum purchase price required will be 20 percent of 
the original amount 
the new law is to take effect on dec 1 ctk said 
privatization of large industrial plants and the agricultural 
sector is expected to begin in early 1991 
</TEXT>
