a terminaly ill man seeking the right to die 
won a court ruling thursday that says doctors must consider his 
request not to be connected to a lifesupport machine should the 
need arise 
tel aviv district court judge uri goren ruled that doctors would 
not face criminal charges if they accepted 50yearold binyamin 
eyals request even if the patient was unconscious at the time 
eyals lawyer shir adonevitch said the ruling could set a 
precedent in israel for the first time a district court 
recognizes the right of a man over his body adonevitch said 
eyals wife pnina told israel radio she was thankful for the 
ruling it manifests the last wish of my husband which is to die 
with honor without any needless torture he has suffered enough 
she said 
the plaintiff sued for the right to order his doctor to avoid 
prolonging his life by artificial means after he loses 
consciousness eyal suffers from amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 
better known as lou gehrigs disease it is an incurable illness 
that causes the breakdown of the muscular system 
dr nahman wilenski who is treating eyal recently told the 
jerusalem post that his patient was having trouble breathing but 
he could not say when he would need a respirator 
the ruling said the decision whether to connect eyal to an 
respirator would be left to the director of the hospital where the 
plaintiff is being treated 
