nearly 3800 rare books and historic 
documents have vanished from the wroclaw university library 
apparently sold abroad under the guise of academic exchanges a 
newspaper reported thursday 
the thefts were discovered early this year by german researchers 
working on the collection that came into polish hands when the 
german city of breslau became the polish city of wroclaw at the end 
of world war ii 
government auditors and the prosecutors office have launched an 
investigation and asked the university rector for disciplinary 
proceedings against library employees as well as to start putting 
the collection in order according to the gazeta wyborcza 
newspaper 
the library houses one of europes largest collections of books 
from the middle ages among its 15 million volumes the newspaper 
said 
auditors said the thefts occurred even after they started their 
inspection of the library 
investigators concluded that traditional interlibrary exchanges 
of books between universities for academic research were being 
exploited for commercial purposes according to gazeta wyborcza 
between 1986 and june 1990 3793 manuscripts were sent abroad 
and sold without appropriate permission the newspaper said 
it said it was impossible to determine the prices the documents 
sold for because the dealings were not recorded by the university 
accounting office 
the customs declarations offer few clues because in 860 cases 
they state the materials were being exported for free exchange and 
did not have cultural value according to the report 
poland has strict laws about exporting pre1945 antiques 
artwork and other items designed to protect the countrys cultural 
heritage 
other investigations have shown however that loose controls on 
museums the financially beleaguered state of cultural 
institutions and abuses by authorities led to the disappearance of 
many treasures from national art and museum collections during the 
communist regime 
the government auditing bureau also suggested the collection was 
not properly cared for because it wasnt polish 
the essential reason for this negligence is an inappropriate 
approach to formerly german collections by both employees of the 
library and the scientific staff of the university the auditing 
bureau said 
