a heathrow airport security officer 
said thursday he received no warning about a bomb threat to pan am 
flight 103 which exploded over lockerbie scotland in 1988 
killing 270 people 
there were no instructions to be on the lookout for a toshiba 
radio cassette recorder among passengers baggage sulkash kumar 
kamboj told a public inquiry into the terrorist bombing the bomb 
that blew up the plane was inside a toshiba cassette recorder 
packed in a suitcase 
kamboj said security staff were told to always check carefully 
any items of electrical equipment among the luggage but he said 
his employers alert security had given him no specific warning to 
look out for the toshiba machine 
he said he knew nothing about the socalled helsinki warning 
of a bomb threat to a pan am flight the us embassy in helsinki 
finland received a telephone warning that there would be a bombing 
attack on a pan am flight from frankfurt to new york around 
christmas but the warning was not made public 
pan american world airways flight 103 originated in frankfurt on 
a boeing 727 but switched to a larger boeing 747 at heathrow for 
the flight to new york 
kamboj said he was working a 12hour day on dec 21 1988 he 
checked passengers luggage being transferred to pan am jets from 
feeder flights at heathrows terminal 3 
all bags transferred from other airlines flights to pan am 
flight 103 passed through an xray machine and he paid particular 
attention to any electrical items but the outline of a 
radiocassette player did not cause special concern among so many 
electrical items kamboj said 
the inquiry heard earlier this week that baggage transferred 
from pan am flights including luggage from frankfurt was not 
screened before being loaded onto the plane scottish police have 
said they believe the bag with the cassette recorder bomb inside 
was put on the plane in frankfurt 
