<TEXT>
the ec commission on thursday granted 
344 million in emergency relief aid for 130000 orphans in 
romania 
the aid will be used to pay for heating fuel at many orphanages 
as well as to provide medicine infant food and spare parts to fix 
some orphanages outoforder heating systems the commission said 
in a statement 
the ec also said it will send an engineer to romania this week 
to assess the need for heating equipment that cannot be bought 
locally 
the funds announced thursday are in addition to 36 million the 
ec granted to nongovernment agencies recently to help care for the 
romanian orphans many of whom are suffering from aids through use 
of infected needles needles have been in chronic short supply in 
romania hence some needles were overused 
the plight of orphans in romania is a legacy of the regime of 
nicolae ceauscescu the former dictator who was executed last 
december 
the commission said it planned another grant of almost 9 
million for additional supplies of infant foods at the request 
of romanias ministry of health 
ec external relations commissioner frans andriessen in a letter 
to romanian prime minister petre roman said the aid granted 
thursday represents the most effective practical solution to 
the immediate heating problem at many orphanages 
in luxembourg last monday the ec and romania signed a fiveyear 
trade and economic cooperation agreement on that occasion roman 
told andriessen that the romanian armed forces had been mobilized 
to help repair heating systems in buildings used as orphanages 
