<TEXT>
the us rift with israel over jerusalem tests 
the bush administrations skill in shielding its middle eastern 
ally from tougher measures in the united nations and in keeping 
flickering hopes for peace talks alive 
us officials said thursday they had no intention of seeking 
new resolutions in the security council attacking israel their 
hope is the furor over israels refusal to cooperate with an 
investigation into the slaying of 19 palestinian arabs will subside 
in a few days 
but secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar said unless israel 
changed its mind his report would deal with ways of protecting 
palestinians and british ambassador david hannay who is presiding 
over the council this month said israels treatment of 
palestinians is not going to go away from the council agenda 
 
that portends a un foot in the door that israeli prime 
minister yitzhak shamir feared and prompted the israeli cabinet to 
refuse to cooperate with the un investigation 
the us vote to deplore israels decision along with a us 
vote two weeks ago to condemn israel for the shootings shatters 
the assumption the united states nearly always stands by its friend 
in the usually hostile united nations 
this could whet the appetite of israels enemies to keep up the 
pressure while diverting the bush administration from its goal of 
refocusing attention on iraqs occupation of kuwait 
the united states and israel used to agree that the un was a 
hostile place that is no longer the case as a result of the end of 
the cold war and now the iraqi aggression said martin indyk 
director of the washington institute for near east policy the 
united states has increasingly turned to the un as the mechanism 
for promoting a new world order while for israel it remains a very 
hostile place 
moreover indyk said thursday that the united states will 
constantly have to decide with every new resolution whether its 
going to isolate itself or condemn israel again this hastens the 
day when either there will be sanctions against israel or the 
united states will have to use its veto so its a nowin situation 
for the united states 
in fact avi pazner spokesman for israeli prime minister 
shamir said thursday that the unanimous resolution helps saddam 
hussenn to distract attention from what is happening in the gulf 
but richard w murphy a former assistant secretary of state for 
the near east faults israel for mishandling the dispute at a 
