hes able to say see thats exactly what ive been saying 
all along follow me and well do something about the palestinian 
issue murphy a senior fellow at the council on foreign 
relations said thursday 
william b quandt who ran the middle east desk at the national 
security council for thenpresident carter says it will be 
difficult for the bush administration to get the focus back on iraq 
at the united nations 
there are pressures in the un largely from the arab group 
and also the third world to bargain over un resolutions to try 
to trade support for us resolutions on the persian gulf for us 
support on arabisraeli issues quandt said thursday 
and yet for the foreseeable future the gulf is so much the 
dominant issue that there is no desire to dwell on this 
difference and its real with israel said quandt who is a 
senior fellow at the brookings institution 
conveniently perhaps next month is the united states turn to 
preside over the security council this could facilitate action on 
a series of resolutions against iraq including a proposal by prime 
minister margaret thatcher of britain that saddam hussein be forced 
to pay reparations for the aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
the israeli cabinets decision and shamirs refusal to reverse 
it is the latest in a string of disagreements with the bush 
administration 
the president has referred to east jerusalem as occupied 
territory thereby suggesting he considers israels control over 
part of its capital illegitimate 
israels settlement of some soviet jewish refugees in east 
jerusalem the west bank and gaza is another sore point 
the bush administration considers settlements of soviet refugees 
or any other jews in the territories an obstacle to peace because 
the arabs hope to recapture the lands they lost in the 1967 mideast 
war 
like its predecessors the administration also is committed to 
urging israel to give up most if not all of the territory in 
exchange for arab acceptance of the jewish state 
david scheffer an international lawyer who is with the carnegie 
endowment for international peace says israel could have admitted 
the un investigators without conceding its claim of sovereignty 
over east jerusalem 
i do not consider it to be giving the un some extraordinary 
foothold in jerusalem he said there are un observers in 
jerusalem the un is already there 
meanwhile secretary of state james a baker iii and others in 
the administration who would like to see israel negotiate with 
palestinians arabs will try to repair the rift before it destroys 
any chance for getting israelipalestinian talks started 
but israel which has depended on us support in a world 
organization largely hostile to the jewish state is bound to feel 
even more anxious about risking negotiations with only the bush 
administration for protection 
does it leave scars exdiplomat murphy said of the two 
us votes against israel probably yes both sides think the 
other is unreasonable 
but asked if the rift derails mideast peace talks murphy 
replied you dont derail something that isnt on the tracks yet 
in fact the tracks arent there yet 
 
editors note barry schweid has covered usisraeli affairs 
for the associated press since 1973 
