<TEXT>
barring the outbreak of war in the persian 
gulf gasoline prices will hover between 130 and 162 per gallon 
over the next year an administration energy expert told a senate 
panel thursday 
the forecast came in the opening session of a threeday hearing 
on why oil prices shoot up on the slightest rumor of trouble in the 
mideast but dont seem to come down on rumors of peace 
us energy information administrator calvin kent also predicted 
that home heating oil would cost between 113 and 145 per gallon 
through 1991 roughly equal to the high levels heating oil reached 
in last winters cold snap 
an improvement in the mideast situation might lower the price of 
crude oil but dont look for an immediate response at the pump 
kent told the senate committee on governmental affairs 
prices go up more quickly than they come down kent said 
the price estimates assume that the persian gulf crisis does not 
dissolve into war that the winter is normal in severity and that 
market factors such as inventories and daily oil production remain 
relatively stable 
also assumed in kents forecast was that crude oil remains at 
about 30 per barrel that assumption seemed open to question even 
as he testified in new yorks mercantile exchange oil jumped 317 
per barrel in early trading to 3425 by mid day 
members of the senate panel focused on the volatility of the oil 
market committee chairman john glenn dohio scoffed at how 
some goofy thing like a rumor about saddam hussein having a 
dream can affect oil prices 
the reference was to a report in an iraqi newspaper that hussein 
had a dream that his guns were aimed at the wrong enemy even the 
mere suggestion that tensions with the united states might be 
reduced was enough to cause crude oil prices to drop 
in the past few days though crude prices have increased as 
hopes for a compromise to end the gulf standoff waned the reason 
for price volatility kent said is that other mideast countries 
like saudi arabia are pumping out extra oil to make up for the loss 
of kuwaiti and iraqi oil further trouble in the mideast could 
interrupt that flow 
the vast amount of replacement oil is coming from the gulf and 
the vast majority of that is coming from saudi arabia kent said 
rumors of war make the market extremely nervous and thats why 
you see these jumps of 2 and 3 in the price based on fairly 
trivial rumors 
american petroleum institute president charles dibona told the 
committee that oil industries have shown considerable restraint 
in holding back on price increases at the pump between aug 2 and 
the end of september he said the spot price on crude oil rose 44 
cents per gallon while gasoline went up at the pump by only 24 
cents 
department of energy statistics submitted to the committee 
indicate that heating oil customers have felt the gulf crisis more 
directly oil companies have passed on 90 percent of the crude 
price increase to consumers of home heating oil 
