<TEXT>
a jury thursday convicted a state lawmaker 
of selling his vote for parimutuel betting for 4300 ending the 
first trial stemming from an fbi undercover sting labeled 
operation lost trust 
the sting so far has resulted in indictments charging 10 
legislators with bribery four have resigned their seats and 
pleaded guilty one of the 10 lawmakers pleaded guilty to drug 
charges earlier this month as did a lobbyist 
the us district court jury convicted state rep luther taylor 
a 40yearold democrat from columbia on all six counts against him 
of violating the hobbs act a federal antibribery law an 
indictment accused him of accepting five separate bribes and with 
conspiring to solicit those bribes in exchange for his support of a 
parimutuel betting bill 
taylor voted for the bill in committee during this past 
legislative session the bill never made it to the state house or 
senate 
the conviction carries a maximum penalty of 120 years in prison 
and a 15 million fine no sentencing date was set 
the jury reached its verdict after about six hours of 
deliberation that followed a 10day trial 
videotapes and lobbyist ron cobb dominated the prosecutions 
case cobb a former democratic house member who had become a 
lobbyist testified that he worked undercover for the fbi after 
getting caught trying to buy cocaine from federal agents 
cobb testified he had bribed taylor with 2500 to help recruit 
other lawmakers to support the parimutuel measure which would 
have allowed voters to decide whether to allow betting on horse and 
dog racing in south carolina 
videotapes showed cobb giving an appreciative taylor the cash 
taylor maintained throughout his testimony that cobb was giving 
him campaign contributions 
but under crossexamination taylor admitted that during a 
january meeting he slipped cobb a note saying for my undivided 
attention 2500 
cobb has been granted immunity another lobbyist james brown 
pleaded guilty to marijuana possession this month in a separate 
case stemming from operation lost trust 
during closing arguments wednesday assistant us attorney dale 
dutremble reminded jurors of the potential impact of their decision 
at the statehouse and around south carolina he said a guilty 
verdict would deter corruption 
how long can you allow people like luther taylor to sell out 
how long can you allow south carolina to be disgraced youre 
entitled to better dutremble said its time for you to send a 
message to the luther taylors of our general assembly 
his office of public trust was for sale dutremble said 
defense attorney joel collins attacked the credibility of 
government witnesses especially cobb 
that ought to bother you that they ought to choose this kind 
of guy collins said 
collins argued four separate defenses to the jury that taylor 
had no intent to break the law that he made a good faith 
effort to obey the law that he did not violate the federal 
antibribery law because he consistently supported the parimutuel 
measure and that his actions could have no effect on interstate 
commerce a required element for a conviction under the law taylor 
was accused of violating 
each one of those defenses should cause the jury to have a 
reasonable doubt that taylor committed the crimes collins 
said 
he said jurors didnt need to convict taylor in order to send a 
message to the statehouse 
if the jury brought back an innocent verdict the message 
wouldnt be we tolerate sleazy legislators the message would be 
dont bring dope dealers in here and expect us to believe them 
beyond a reasonable doubt 
us attorney bart daniel got the last word in the prosecutions 
rebuttal 
he reminded the jury that taylor admitted having more 
enthusiasm for the parimutuel betting bill after he got 2500 
from cobb 
can you imagine a public official testifying on the stand that 
he could be more enthusiastic for 2500 or 500 or 300 
daniel asked 
</TEXT>
