<TEXT>
federal regulators approved on thursday a plan 
to sell or close about 192 failed savings and loan institutions 
over the next six months 
the proposed action which involves assets valued at 119 
billion is part of an operating plan for the resolution trust 
corporation established to oversee the bailout of the financially 
devastated thrift industry 
officials of the rtc oversight board approved the new plan they 
said its implementation would bring to about 479 the total number 
of thrifts whose financial problems have been resolved by 
liquidation or other actions since aug 9 1989 
but they noted that the plan is subject to the congressional 
appropriations process and cannot be completed unless it receives 
full financing 
under the plan the trust corporations oversight board would 
authorize 622 billion in new financing 
this would include 23 billion to resolve the financial problems 
of the 192 savings institutions and 389 billion in working 
capital to be borrowed through the federal financing bank 
the rtc has proposed an ambitious plan for the first six 
months of fiscal 1991 which began on oct 1 which will allow it 
to continue a high level of resolutions said peter h monroe 
the president of the oversight board 
if the rtc meets its target of 192 new resolutions it will 
have sold or closed approximately 90 percent of all thrifts seized 
by the rtc to date monroe said 
the oversight board sets policy approves the financing and 
provides general oversight supervision for the resolution trust 
corp in its task of liquidating the nations failed savings and 
loan associations 
