<DOCNO> AP901025-0159 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
monthly injections of a newly approved drug for 
treating endometriosis could help hundreds of thousands of women 
who have the fertilitythreatening condition doctors said 
thursday 
the drug a prostatecancer medicine called lupron depot is 
already commonly prescribed for endometriosis doctors know it 
works to reverse the malady and relieve its sometimes debilitating 
pain gynecologists said 
but the government had not approved its use for treating 
anything other than prostate cancer and insurance companies refused 
to cover its costs 252 for monthly injections which are 
typically administered for six months doctors said 
its a drug thats welltolerated its side effects are 
minimal and its an exciting development that we now have 
approval said dr gary a shangold associate professor of 
obstetrics and gynecology at the university of chicago 
he spoke at a press confeence held by the manufacturer tap 
pharmaceuticals the deerfieldbased company said it was notified 
monday that the us food and drug administration had approved 
lupron depot for treating endometriosis 
the drug suppresses production of the female hormone estrogen 
which controls growth of the tissue that lines the womb called the 
endometrium 
endometriosis occurs when that tissue migrates outside the womb 
usually into the abdomen and pelvis where it swells and bleeds 
during menstruation if it develops in the ovaries or fallopian 
tubes it can cause blockage scarring and infertility 
an estimated 2 million to 5 million women have endometriosis 
which may be mild and symptom free but the condition also may 
cause severe menstrual cramps pain during sexual intercourse 
painful urination or painful bowel movements 
side effects of lupron depot resemble those of menopause 
including hot flashes but are not permanent and may be relieved 
with other medication 
in essence what were doing is creating a temporary 
medically induced menopause a reversible menopause that in turn 
stops the stimulation of the endometriosis said dr james 
miller medical director at tap 
the company is a joint venture between japanese pharmaceutical 
company takeda chemical industries and north chicagobased abbott 
laboratories 
other doctors said the approval should open the way for using 
the drug for a variety of gynecological problems such as 
premenstrual syndrome uterine fibroid tumors and even benign 
breast tumors 
i think its very significant dr robert l barbieri 
chairman of obstetrics and gynecology at state university of new 
york at stony brook said of thursdays announcement 
he estimated it could help up to onethird of women who have 
endometriosis including by heading off surgery 
barbieri said the only other drugs approved for treating 
endometriosis are synarel a nasal spray that costs about the same 
as lupron depot and danazol a derivative of the male hormone 
testosterone that costs about half as much 
synarel requires twice daily doses for six months and is poorly 
absorbed by the body barbieri said danazol causes women to 
develop male traits a deepening of the voice facial hair oilier 
skin and upper body muscles he said 
as for lupron depot the main down side of the drug is it does 
cause a low estrogen state and it may cause thinning of vertebral 
bones barbieri said he said further study will be necessary to 
determine whether the amount of bone thinning is significant 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

