<TEXT>
the soviet union said thursday that its 
employees in the united nations no longer must pay part of their 
salaries to moscow which for decades reportedly used the hard 
currency to fund espionage 
the announcement by deputy foreign minister valentin nikiforov 
was a concession to reality soviet un workers rebelled against 
the soviet missions control this summer and many refused to turn 
over their paychecks 
a un administrative tribunal ruled that most of their 
contracts which gave moscow the right to require then to return 
home in two to four years were invalid that freed the soviet 
employees to seek independent un contracts 
soviet employees indicated the threat of being returned home was 
used for years to force them to accept soviet payment terms 
the un tribunal also invalidated many shortterm contracts of 
chinese un employees it ruled that staffers with five years or 
more experience could apply directly to the world body to renew 
their contracts 
for years chinese soviet and other eastern european workers at 
the united nations have had to turn over their paychecks to their 
countries un missions the soviets lost about 40 percent of the 
value of their pay this way 
soviet employees said the soviet mission paid their rent and 
gave them monthly allowances of 1000 to 1400 keeping the rest 
rossen vassilev a former bulgarian un employee who defected 
in 1988 said soviet bloc nations recycled the confiscated cash to 
fund espionage in the west 
soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze said in 1988 that 
moscow would let some soviets apply for longterm un contracts 
the soviet mission said only about 10 soviet professionals have 
accepted permanent contracts so far 
but nikiforov said all soviets would be permitted to seek 
longterm contracts starting jan 1 
the soviet union has about 450 staffers in the secretariat in 
new york and overseas about 500 other soviets work in 
unaffiliated agencies in geneva rome vienna paris nairobi 
montreal and washington almost all work on shortterm contracts 
