hundreds of people line up at the tsum 
department store to buy scarce rationed food at a luxury hotel 
nearby westerners with hard currency enjoy the best of food and 
wine 
long food lines reflect an economic crisis that is aggravating 
social tensions and forcing a traditionally agrarian nation to beg 
for food from the west to get through the winter 
the government has proposed a 300day moratorium on public 
rallies to keep consumer anger from getting out of hand 
diplomats in sofia said they did not expect food riots 
immediately but an energy shortage means the worst is yet to come 
the soviet union has reduced oil shipments to bulgaria and un 
sanctions have halted supplies from iraq 
at the congress in september of the governing socialist party 
the new name of the communist party some officials spoke of unrest 
or civil war 
even without civil unrest prospects are gloomy president 
zhelyu zhelev denies reports that bulgaria faces starvation but 
acknowledged recently that poverty is a fact 
food stores in sofia and other cities are virtually bare sugar 
cheese flour eggs cooking oil and detergent are rationed 
as in romania and the soviet union such ordinary items as light 
bulbs toilet paper and matches are as scarce as food 
about 500 people waited outside tsum one october morning a 
