<TEXT>
from live reports on the invasion of 
europe to the medical advice of the goatgland doctor its still 
all there for anyone to hear and the good thing is anyone can 
hear it 
the history in sound dating back to the 1920s is available 
through more than 3800 radio broadcasts on file at memphis state 
university 
while the collection is not the largest of its kind its 
certainly one of the most accessible unlike most radio archives 
it isnt just open to broadcasting students and researchers any 
radio fan can drop by to listen to a little abbott and costello or 
perhaps a bit of inner sanctum 
not only can you hear it if you bring an audio cassette with 
you theyll highspeed duplicate it for you said marvin 
bensman founder and chief overseer of the collection 
an associate professor of broadcast history bensman began 
putting the collection together in 1969 while working at the 
university of vermont 
his students he said had little access to early radio 
broadcasts except through such sources as the national archives in 
washington 
thats sort of ridiculous to ask a college student to pay his 
way to washington to listen to some old radio programs for a 
course he said 
from a variety of sources including former broadcasters or 
their families bensman has put more than 1200 radio hours on 
tape 
theres a 1949 pilot of gunsmoke starring mark thats 
right mark dillon and worldsaving battles between the shadow 
and various forces of evil fibber mcgee and molly build a doghouse 
or search for lost keys while j edgar hoover warns of creeping 
communism 
the collection includes several hours of live coverage of the 
allied invasion of europe when the outcome of world war ii and the 
fate of the world was very much unsettled 
everyone was hanging on their radios to see were we going to 
make it bensman said 
it also includes a series of shows by dr jospeh r brinkley an 
almostgovernor of kansas who broadcast medical advice in the 1920s 
and 30s brinkley picked up the nickname goat gland doctor 
because of claims he could improve the sex lives of his male 
patients with animal implants bensman said 
he did a 90minute program where you would write him and 
describe your symptoms he would then diagnose your problem and 
prescribe to you over the air he said 
raising the ire of the american medical association and the 
federal radio commission brinkley lost his broadcasting license in 
milford kan he moved to mexico and set up a hospital straddling 
the usmexican border 
he was a real pioneer bensman said his voice is 
wonderful on the radio ive listened to the stuff and his advice 
is not bad 
a stack of 16inch recording discs of brinkleys show were 
recently found in the attic of his widow bensman said 
while academic researchers and biographers of radio 
personalities often use bensmans radio collection it can also 
come in handy for such people as the daughter of the 
silvermasked tenor 
the tenor whose real name was josh white performed on a radio 
show sponsored by a tire company in the 1920s to promote 
silvertone tires program managers staged a yearlong contest 
featuring an unnamed singer said to be wearing a silver mask 
listeners were urged to guess his identity 
whites daughter contacted bensman looking for a recording of 
her fathers voice and a performance by the silvermasked tenor 
was found on one of his tapes 
we sent a tape and she was overjoyed bensman said 
the older programs in the collection are on 16inch discs which 
can hold up to 15 minutes on each side the broadcasts are put on 
reeltoreel tapes and then on the cassettes that are made 
available to the public 
the collection continues to grow as more old programs are 
located and as modern ones are added to keep up with the evolution 
of radio 
bensman said he has a list of 60 to 70 programs he still seeks 
from the early days of radio 
when we get those we think well have every known program 
that ever appeared on the networks he said 
the sought after shows include such programs as eyes aloft 
its a program about air travel or being in the air force i 
think bensman said its hard to say nobody has heard these 
programs in years 
