<TEXT>
author james conaway calls napa valley an 
american eden which turns out to be an apt description of his 
book about sex scandal and sweat among families who built northern 
californias famous wineries 
this is a real place these are real people in my book 
conaway said about his book napa houghton mifflin 2495 
i get as personal as i can because thats the way you write good 
books there are many strong characters and this is the first time 
their story has been told 
his book reads like fiction as the people behind napa valleys 
most famous labels inglenook krug schram beaulieu martini and 
mondavi come to life 
the mondavis robert and peter could be the warring cain and 
abel without the fratricide following a 1965 fist fight between 
the two brothers who ran the charles krug winery peter and the 
family fired robert who went on to start the robert mondavi 
winery 
robert mondavis two sons michael and timothy now run the 
successful operation 
everybody talked to me but ive heard that some people are a 
bit bothered by the book the author said theyre not used to 
being written about in this way they lead lives that have so far 
been unexamined 
volker eisele who has grown grapes in the valley for the past 
20 years said the book is accurate and gives a behindthescenes 
glimpse to people who arent players in napa 
ive been hearing through the grapevine that a few people are 
unhappy about how hey came out maybe it turned out to be too 
personal he said 
conaway does get past the doors and cellars of napas wineries 
spending some time in the bedrooms but tales of infidelities dont 
get much ink 
occasionally someone got into bed with someone elses mate 
but bridge was the preferred activity he says in the book 
still conaway doesnt shy away from telling about betty daniel 
who despite her mormon upbringing was often unfaithful to husband 
john daniel who inherited inglenook from his father 
john had economic muscle in the valley and twice got rid 
of bettys lovers by depriving them of jobs but there was always a 
replacement conaway writes of the daniels who eventually 
divorced 
daniel was among the old families in the lush napa valley which 
saw the first planting of grapes in the 1830s after george yount 
settled the area until then the dust and fogfilled valley some 
50 miles north of san francisco had been inhabited only by wappo 
indians 
in 1858 a german named charles krug began a napa valley wine 
business using native mission grapes german varieties were soon 
thriving in the area along with vintners such as frederick 
beringer and jacob schram 
the germanborn founders were anglosaxons with mediterranean 
delusions if truth be told conaway writes 
interest in wines of the region increased during the 1880s and 
90s when inglenook was built at the height of a silver mining 
boom along the silverado trail 
prohibition the depression and world war ii put a cork in the 
winery business some however survived newcomers such as the 
christian brothers the louis martini family and the mondavi family 
even prospered 
at that time the italian vintners didnt care as much for 
quality in wine as for quantity their product was sold in jugs 
conaway writes 
during the early 50s and 60s interest in napa valley was 
rekindled with speciality wineries starting up and decrepit 
properties being renovated 
the leaders of the latest renaissance included refugees from 
business academia and totalitarianism and some colorful 
misfits 
by the mid70s when northern california wines started beating 
french wines in taste tests napa valleys boom was on every 
winery had a tasting room and tourists many on bicycles began 
traveling valley road en masse 
enter politics 
in the last few chapters of napa conaways historical 
narrative turns into a cautionary tale about the dangers of 
overdevelopment about 250 wineries now crowd napa valley and 
nearby sonoma valley compared with just a few dozen 30 years ago 
and a touristy railroad the wine train runs through the area 
some would seek to turn the land into tourist attractions 
with the valley taking on a gloss that had more to do with money 
than with the product for which it became famous conaway writes 
in 1988 napa county supervisors approved an ordinance that 
requires wines from napa valley to be made with at least 75 percent 
valley grapes now the county is grappling with how much growth to 
allow with grape growers urging preservation as vintners push 
expansion 
i think the future is undetermined at this point conaway 
said in an interview i see napa as a kind of agricultural 
yosemite that doesnt need too much government protection but it 
should be allowed to endure 
