as civil war in the countryside reaches closer to the capital 
its just total chaos a western aid administrator said 
civil administration has broken down almost totally the 
government is virtually in a state of collapse 
gunfire is heard in the city every night bombs explode and 
armed robbery is so frequent that nearly everyone has a tale to 
tell of an assault on his own or someone elses home 
the robberies are blamed on soldiers who are said to supplement 
their meager pay with nightly forays into residential neighborhoods 
darkened by lack of electricity 
everyone is arming themselves out of fear an aid worker 
said on condition of anonymity you can buy an assault rifle or 
pistol on almost any street corner soldiers are selling them on 
the black market 
thousands of refugees from fighting in the northern central and 
southern parts of somalia compound mogadishus miseries many live 
with family members in the city stretching household budgets to 
the breaking point 
a middlerank civil servant is paid 10000 somali shillings a 
month the equivalent of about 3 in a land where hyperinflation 
has sent the price of a beer to 2000 shillings 
we have a great tradition of sharing said mohamoud s nur 
a former adviser to president mohamed siad barre if i have 
something and you have nothing i share what i have with you its 
the only way people survive these days 
the problem is there is increasingly less to share its 
getting desperate there is real hunger in mogadishu real 
deprivation real suffering 
nur 54 is a sign of the changing times a critic of the 
