only to the first 51300 earned each year the bill would raise it 
to 125000 or 130000 
a worker earning 85000 a year for example would pay 1233 
or 489 more than present law a 50000 earner would pay no more 
the tax is matched by the employer 
the bill would limit the total of certain itemized deductions 
that a person with income over 100000 or a couple over 150000 
may write off but the 3 percent limitation would apply only 
against income above those levels 
for each 10000 of income above the target the proposal would 
reduce allowable deductions by 300 thus a couple with 175000 
income and itemized deductions of 35000 would be allowed to write 
off only 34250 
this has the effect of raising the 31 percent top tax rate for 
these people to 32 percent 
the bill also would gradually take back from the welltodo the 
tax saving realized from personal exemptions this would result in 
larger highincome families paying a higher marginal tax rate than 
those with fewer children a notion under attack as a tax on 
children 
for 1990 a taxpayer is allowed a 2050 exemption for himself 
and another for each dependent at the 31 percent top tax rate set 
by the bill that would mean a tax saving of 636 per exemption 
single people would begin losing part of that 636 tax saving 
once their taxable income income after subtracting deductions and 
exemptions passes 100000 the benefit would be lost totally 
when income hits 225000 for couples who file jointly and have no 
children the benefit would be phased out between 150000 and 
275000 of income 
the effect of the phaseout would be to boost the top tax rate on 
these taxpayers by onehalf of a percentage point thus the limit 
on deductions and the exemption phaseout would raise the top rate 
to 325 percent for a single person and 33 percent for a couple 
a couple with two children could have a top rate of 34 percent 
on part of their earnings a couple with six children could pay 36 
percent 
