blaming higher jet fuel costs and other factors delta air lines 
and usair group reported losses thursday while ual said its 
earnings dropped 4 percent 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
for the first fiscal quarter ended sept 30 atlantabased delta 
reported a loss of 516 million or 127 per share on operating 
revenue of 222 billion that compared with aftertax profit of 
1331 million or 253 per share on revenue of 217 billion in 
the same period last year 
this is the first loss delta has had in a september quarter 
since 1982 thomas j roeck jr senior vice president and chief 
financial officer said referring to the busy summer travel months 
roeck attributed the loss to the increase in jet fuel prices 
since the iraqi invastion of kuwait the increase added 781 
million to deltas expenses 
he also blamed softening demand and competition from eastern 
saying passenger revenue increased just 2 percent in the quarter 
if these trends continue the company expects to report a loss 
for the full calendar year roeck said 
delta spokesman bill berry said the company set aside 10 
million to be tapped if any of its competitors go out of business 
when an airline has to book a passenger on another carrier the fare 
difference goes into a pool that could be jeopardized by a 
bankruptcy 
for the first nine months deltas aftertax profits totaled 
538 million or 85 cents per share on operating revenue of 66 
billion that compared with earnings of 4089 million or 812 
per share on revenue of 65 billion for the same period last 
year 
</TEXT>
